\chapter{Land use and urban planning}
\label{chap:land_use_urban_planning}
%#############################################################

\epigraph{The truth about a city's aspirations isn't found in its vision. 
It's found in its budget.}{Brent Toderian}

The previous three chapters described sustainability challenges related to 
households, transportation, and food.
A common element in all these sustainability challenges is how we use land.
We need \emph{places} for homes, to grow food, and for transportation systems. 
Moreover, where we choose to put each of these elements influences 
the overall need for transportation in human society.
For example, dwellings and businesses that are spread out across a large area will
require more transportation than if they were located close together.

This chapter examines two aspects of land use.
The first aspect is the layout or arrangement of different uses of land.
Which is more sustainable: to group all the farms, forests, and cities so that 
each is as large as possible?
Or is it better to intersperse many small farms, forests, and towns?
Whereas Chapter~\ref{chap:households} was concerned 
with the sustainability of individual housing units,
this chapter considers dwellings and businesses collectively. 
%The objective is to design cities and farms with sustainability in mind.
We consider the sustainability implications of spacing, density, and how 
transportation links between locations are affected by layout.

The second aspect is allocation, that is, \emph{how much} of each of the 
different uses for land we have.
Land can be used for agriculture, recreation, urban or suburban dwellings, or 
not allocated for direct human use, that is, left as wilderness.
Land is the source, directly or indirectly, for all our resources, the sink for
much of our waste, and where we ourselves live.
We need land to simultaneously satisfy many different wants and needs,
including supplying resources, accepting wastes, and providing ecosystem services.

The next sections deal with three major sustainability questions related to land use: 
How do we use land?
How does our use of land affect sustainability?
How can we transition to more sustainable ways of using land?


%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Demand for land use}
\label{sec:land_and_how_it_is_used}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

Equation~\ref{eq:IPARX} shows two main drivers for land use:
population (\mft{P}, Chapter~\ref{chap:population}) and
affluence (\:\!\mft{A}, Chapter~\ref{chap:affluence}).
The remaining two terms on the right-hand side of Equation~\ref{eq:IPARX} (\mft{R} and \mft{X})
are fixed by technology. 
The size of the economy is \mft{P}$\times$\mft{A}.
The economy can grow by increasing either \mft{P} or \mft{A}.
The next two sections will examine these sources of demand in greater detail.

