%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Population \Pparen{}}
\label{sec:land_demand_population}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

Figure~\ref{fig:USlanduse} shows how land is used in the United States. 
There are nearly 2.3 billion acres in the U.S.
Of this total, agriculture takes the largest share, with grassland (29\%), 
forestry (28\%), and cropland (17\%) being the three largest uses.%
\footnote{
  Land used for grazing includes grassland, cropland used for pasture, and grazed forest land. 
  Forestry is forest that is not grazed. 
  Crop production is 87\% of total cropland; the remaining 13\% is idle or used for pasture.
}
%
The four largest crops in the U.S. are wheat (32\% of total crops), corn (30\%),
soybeans (20\%), and cotton (10\%). 
All other crops combined account for only 8\% of total crops.
In contrast, the area where we live and work
is a relatively small 70 million acres (3\%).
The U.S. is relatively sparsely populated.

%-----------------------------
\paragraph{Agriculture}
%-----------------------------

As mentioned in Chapter~\ref{chap:agriculture}, population drives agriculture,
and agriculture is \emph{the} most prevalent way we use land.
As world population has grown, the additional humans have been fed (in part) by
converting more land to agriculture over time.

%-----------------------------
\paragraph{Urban areas}
%-----------------------------

Population growth also leads directly to a need for more housing,
but not just any housing.
Another trend shown by land-use statistics is greater urbanization.
The demand for housing is disproportionately for urban housing
because of a long-term trend of migration to urban areas. 
Urban areas have much higher GDP per area.
Thus, pursuit of wealth, that is, a desire for greater affluence~\Aparen{}, drives 
migration from rural areas to urban ones.

%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Affluence \Aparen{}}
\label{sec:land_demand_affluence}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
In contrast to the needs for food and housing, which are proportional to the population,
affluence is not directly tied to population.
Any given population could have any level of affluence.
The economy, as society's metabolism, ingests resources (particularly energy) and
excretes wastes.

%-----------------------------
\paragraph{Resources}
%-----------------------------

Land is the primary source of energy, be it fossil fuel, biomass, or renewable. 
Wells or mines for fossil fuels are located in a \emph{place}.
Biomass has to be grown or harvested from a \emph{place} as well.
For example, about 30\% of the U.S. corn (maize) crop is converted into ethanol
to be blended with gasoline as a transportation fuel.
Renewables, such as hydro, solar photovoltaic, and wind power, are also located in
\emph{places}.
In particular, for hydro, solar, and wind, correct siting is a key consideration
for how productive each power type will be.
Not all locations are suitable for hydro power. Or wind. Or solar.

In addition to energy, the economy needs material resources;
see Figures~\ref{fig:total_material_use} and~\ref{fig:per_capita_material_use}.
A major example is timber, which is a key ingredient in construction and many
consumer goods.
Figure~\ref{fig:USlanduse} shows that growing timber is a major use of U.S.\ land.

A major cause of deforestation in the Amazon basin, for instance, is 
extraction of mineral wealth
because there is a strong demand for resources~\Rparen{} to feed an ever-growing global 
economy.
Those on the lowest rungs of the socio-economic ladder have few options to 
improve their lives. 
They need places to live, food to eat, and income to purchases these and other goods.
They can move to urban areas to try to get work or they can try to extract (pun intended)
a living by farming or mining.
Unfortunately, the best lands have already been taken; what is available to the 
\emph{next} farmer or miner is typically of marginally \emph{lower} productivity.

%-----------------------------
\paragraph{Ecosystem services}
%-----------------------------
Because energy use and carbon emissions are the prime example in this book,
and because land plays a crucial role in regulating carbon in the environment,
this section examines the capacity of the land to absorb and store carbon.

Land is a major carbon sink. 
Forests store a lot of carbon and reforestation is likely necessary for meeting
climate change limits, which makes continued \emph{deforestation} particularly 
alarming.
Land use affects, and is affected by, climate change. 
For instance, hotter, drier weather results in more frequent and severe wildfires.
Those fires destroy forests, release stored carbon, and contribute to further warming.

