the ecosystem services needed to eliminate the wastes produced by economic activity
(\mft{P}$\times$\mft{A}$\times$\mft{R}$\times$\mft{X}).


%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Sustainability challenges in land use and urban planning}
\label{sec:land_sustainability_challenges}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

Humans' use of the land has changed over time. 
Tracking those changes is important for understanding relationships between
land use and sustainability challenges (for example, climate change).
The data for surveys such as Figure~\ref{fig:USlanduse} are produced from satellite imagery.
The European Space Agency recently released a dataset for \emph{global} land use over
a 24-year period (1992-2015) as part of a climate change initiative (CCI).
The Inter-governmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC) uses 9 categories for land-use
classification: 
agriculture, forest, grass, wetland, settlement, shrubland, sparse, bare, and water.
Humans altered almost 1\% of total land area per year (22\% in 24 years~\cite{Nowosad2019})
across all land-use categories.

This section examines sustainability challenges related to the way humans use land
for housing, for transportation, and for agriculture.

%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Housing or urban sustainability}
\label{sec:land_challenges_housing}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

Two sustainability challenges related to urban areas are their tendency to grow 
continually and the need to continually repair depreciating infrastructure.
(Note that these two challenges are not the only ones cities face; they are just
the ones we have chosen to highlight as examples in this chapter. 
Other challenges include, for instance, the ever-increasing need to water to supply
a growing urban population and the need to mitigate the effects of climate change.
As an example of the latter, several cities have already appointed ``extreme heat
officials.'')


\paragraph{Urban sprawl}
Analysis~\cite{Nowosad2019} of the CCI data reveals some trends related to land use change over time.
One trend is that urban areas are continually growing and, basically, never shrink.
From 1992--2015, settlements gained 337,000 square kilometers, which is 0.23\%
of the Earth's land area, or about 0.01\% per year.
Fundamentally, urban areas can't continue to grow forever.
If the Earth's surface were 100\% urban, where would we store carbon, grow food, or obtain material
and energy resources?

The source of land for urban growth is principally agricultural land that is near 
urban areas.
However, to feed a growing population, \emph{net} agricultural land has had to 
increase. 
The increase comes, primarily, from forests being converted to agriculture.
Simultaneously, there is also some (formerly) agricultural land being
reforested.
The net gain for agricultural land means that \emph{more} forests are cleared
than the amount of agricultural land that is being reforested.

The conversion of forest to agricultural land to urban environments has several 
sustainability implications.
First, there is a net loss of \emph{high-quality} agricultural land.
As existing farms near cities become urban areas, agricultural activities are pushed 
out to more marginal land.
Second, the net effect is deforestation, which results in greenhouse gas emissions.
Land use and land-use change are an important source of anthropogenic greenhouse gas emissions.

A sustainability challenge associated with urban growth is
``how can cities supply the needs of an increasing and increasingly urban population?''
There are challenges associated with the city's systems, for example, power, sanitation,
and water supply. 
There are also challenges with respect to continual and continued growth.
Cities have been converting agricultural land to urban environments for centuries.
In the last century, that trend has only accelerated.
``How can the best farmland be preserved for future food production?''


\paragraph{Infrastructure sustainability}
Urban areas are defined by a relative abundance of public works.
A rural road might have a drainage ditch beside the road but the road itself
might not be paved. 
In contrast, a suburban street will be paved and have gutters, curbs, storm sewers, and a sidewalk.
A city center will additionally have public buildings such as a courthouse, library,
post office, parks, and, perhaps, bridges.
Eventually, all the above infrastructure will reach the end of its functional life
and have to be repaired or replaced.
To remain a city, enough taxes have to be collected over the infrastructure's life
to repair or replace it when it wears out.
To be sustainable, an urban area has to be valuable enough to generate the additional
revenue to pay for its additional infrastructure.
\href{https://www.strongtowns.org/}{StrongTowns.org} discusses sustainable 
infrastructure financing in more detail.

Cities face additional sustainability challenges related to infrastructure lifespan, 
economic and population growth, changing technology, and fractured ownership.
The design lifetime of infrastructure may not match its economic lifetime.
Population growth might make a bridge with a 100-year lifespan inadequate to 
satisfy transportation demand after only 30 years.
Wireless communication technologies have rendered wire-based communication much
less relevant. 
However, when changes are necessary, often the multiple constraints of urban environments
make upgrading infrastructure costly and difficult. 
That is, transitions are especially difficult for cities.

A sustainability challenge associated with urban infrastructure is
``how can cities cost effectively modernize infrastructure to accept growth, 
be resilient to climate change, require less energy, and provide for human needs?"

%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Transportation}
\label{sec:land_challenges_transportation}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

Transportation is a vital element in making urban areas valuable and functional. 
Another way of thinking about the role of transportation in urban environments is
that transportation creates places worth going to.
Consider, for example, an urban restaurant that serves very tasty food. 
If you can't get to it, it doesn't matter how good the food is. 
The potential customer base is restricted to the number of people that can get 
to the restaurant.
Access becomes both an economic enabler and an economic multiplier.

% maintaining infrastructure.
Perhaps ironically, the transportation itself is \emph{not} something people want 
to visit. 
No one ever said, ``Hey, let's go sit next to the freeway and watch it for the 
afternoon.''
Rail yards, bus stations, and airports are loud, and often uncomfortable, places to be.
A desirable city center is pleasant, walkable, human scale, and space efficient.
Being desirable makes urban areas valuable, which, in turn, creates the tax base 
to sustain infrastructure. 

In 2018, just 31 counties (out of 3141, or under 1\%)produced 32\% of U.S. GDP. 
% https://www.visualcapitalist.com/america-land-use/
Most of these were around major U.S.\ metropolitan areas, such as New York City,
Los Angeles, or Chicago.
A large part of the value of cities comes from the concentration of people,
who are both a resource and a market.
A large pool of labor allows access to specialized skills and a quantity of labor
to create large and valuable products, like aircraft, microchip foundries, or 
sophisticated software.
Conversely, a large population of consumers allows specialized markets to develop
that would not have enough appeal to be viable in a rural or small-town setting.
Examples include specialty grocery stores, a school for ballroom dance, or an exotic pet store.

For a fixed population density, a city can only grow its population by expanding.
% (By the way, population density is %strongly influenced)
% determined by local building codes and zoning regulations.)
As ``rings'' are added to the city and the diameter of the city grows, the time
it takes to travel across the city grows as well. 
At some point, the city diameter becomes so big that it becomes infeasible to 
travel from some parts of the city to other parts.
At that point, the economic benefits of growing are lost: the markets can't
reach each other.
The city has reached its effective limit.
Therefore, the role and value of transportation is key to the economic success
of a city.
Effective transportation and population density are, in some sense, two sides
of the same coin. 
Higher population densities means transportation is less important. 
Lower population densities means transportation is needed even more.
Figure~\ref{fig:urban_density} illustrates the point by showing the relationship 
between urban density and transport-related energy consumption.
Clearly, there is a tradeoff between urban density and cost of transportation.

