%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Agriculture}
\label{sec:land_challenges_agriculture}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

In contrast to the sustainability challenges associated with agriculture that 
were discussed in Section~\ref{sec:ag_sust_challenges}, the focus of this chapter
is not on the inputs and outputs of agricultural operations. 
Instead, the focus is about the sustainability of land-use patterns for agriculture.

As has been mentioned already, conversion of agricultural land to other uses, particularly
urban areas is a challenge. 
Humans have been practicing agriculture for millenia. 
The most fertile, most productive locations have already been identified. 
The challenge is keeping those most productive locations as agriculture and not
allocating them other other uses, such as housing.

%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Sustainability transitions in land use and urban spaces}
\label{sec:land_sustainability_improvements}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

This chapter began by asking two important questions about land use: how much of 
each type of land use should we have and
what is the best layout?
One obvious answer to the first question is ``as much as we need,''
The question of allocation therefore becomes a question of land use efficiency. 
How can we adequately meet our needs \emph{as efficiently as possible}?
To put it another way, how can we meet our food, housing, and resource needs
while using as little land as possible?

%+++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++
\subsection{Land use efficiency}
\label{sec:land_efficiency}
%+++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

Because land is a limited resource, 
it makes sense to maximize the effective use 
of that resource, whether that's for food, housing, and/or ecosystem services.
Various metrics (only some related to sustainability)
could be used to gauge the effectiveness of land use
in agricultural settings or in cities.
From a environmental sustainability point of view, 
we could try to maximize 
biodiversity, wilderness area, air and water quality, or 
ecosystem services and
the health of the environment that provides those ecosystem services.

\paragraph{Urban land-use efficiency}
For urban land uses, we could attempt to
maximize population density,
we could minimize metrics related to environmental impact, or 
we could try to make cities as self-sufficient as 
possible, for example with respect to food or energy.
We might try to minimize the amount of transportation emissions within cities.
Or we might try to maximize urban GDP.

Since a growing urban population is expected to put unprecedented demand on cities 
and city services, high population density is will help to answer this challenge.
First, higher densities lessen the need to expand the physical footprint of the urban
area. 
Second, higher densities will lessen the cost of infrastructure per area.

\paragraph{Agriculture land-use efficiency}
For agricultural land uses, we could attempt to maximize
calories per acre, pounds of food per acre, number of people fed per acre, 
\emph{or} the EROI of agriculture. 
Ultimately, agriculture has to feed people, so both minimizing the amount of land
required to do that and maximizing the EROI will be help humanity to become more
sustainable.

Because of the climate crisis, it seems clear that significantly more carbon needs to
be removed from the atmosphere and stored somewhere. 
Figure~\ref{fig:CarbonStorage} indicates that agriculture can play an important
role in sequestering carbon from the atmosphere, particularly in grasslands and
croplands.
Indeed, agriculture \emph{must} become a carbon sink, instead of a carbon source,
if we are to be sustainable.

