\paragraph{Resource extraction}
Figure~\ref{fig:PowerDensity} shows the land use requirements for different forms of
energy. 
If we are going to make an energy transition to renewable sources 
(WWS, Section~\ref{sec:low_carbon_transition}), 
Figure~\ref{fig:PowerDensity} shows that we will need to devote a lot more land
to energy production.
Since the amount of land is fixed, either we have to combine energy generation
with other activities \emph{or} we have to reduce the amount of land dedicated, say,
agriculture and forestry.
Since \emph{more} forest and grassland is needed to store carbon, the latter does not
seem like a viable option.

There are two options for the former that are promising. 
The first of these is rooftop solar. 
Through a combination of energy efficiency and generation, each building could be
made energy self-sufficient.
The second option is a combination of solar electricity generation with agriculture for
crops that prefer some shade, like coffee and raspberries.
Still, at least with the current technology, there is an imbalance in the amount of
generating capacity needed for a fully zero-carbon economy and land available for 
generating that electricity.

%^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
\begin{mcframe}[0.90\textwidth](0.85\textwidth)
%^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
Many of the ``good'' uses for land are in tension with each other, 
and the tension between land use for human needs and
preservation of ecosystem services is particularly acute. 
One way to describe the tension between human use and preservation
is sparing versus sharing~\cite{Fraanje2018}.
Land ``sparing'' seeks to minimize the amount of agricultural land needed for humans
but maximizing the productivity of that land, even if it means input-intensive farming
that results in less biodiversity \emph{on the farm}. 
Other land is ``spared'' and set aside for conservation.
Land ``sharing'' uses agricultural practices that are more eco-friendly to wildlife
species on the farm, but, because yields aren't as high, requires more total farm land.

Improving sustainability means increasing the ``sparing'' (for instance, to combat
extinction rate) and increasing the ``sharing.'' 
How can we do both better?
\end{mcframe}

%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
\section{Summary}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

Like energy, land use is also a nexus for many sustainability challenges.
This chapter explored sustainability issues associated with urban areas,
agricultural land-use patterns, and the role of land in provisioning resources
for the economy and removing wastes (notably, carbon) from the ecosystem.
Population growth and migration to urban areas (in search of greater affluence)
is driving an increase in the demand for urban and agricultural land. 
Higher population densities and greater agricultural productivity can help meet
that demand. 
In contrast, Figure~\ref{fig:PowerDensity} indicates it may need be possible to
meet the energy needs of the future solely with renewables because there may not
be enough land.

The next two chapters discuss some collective and individual actions that can be
taken to address these, and other, sustainability challenges.

