\section*{Questions}\index{questions}
\markright{Questions}
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

\begin{questions}

\item Consider the process of creating more land. 
      Typically, a coastal area is ``filled in,'' turning ocean or wetland into 
      dry ground. 
      For example, an airport in a coastal city might extend its runways into the 
      ocean to accommodate more traffic or larger aircraft. 
      What are the environmental, social, and economic tradeoffs?
      Do you think future generations will be happy to have the land or shaking
      their heads at what was done to our (their) coastline?
      
\item Research indicates that if a farmer's land amount is below a certain threshold
      it can create a ``poverty trap''~\cite{Coomes2011}.
      There is just enough land for subsistence farming but alternatives to 
      farming can't generate enough income to escape poverty.
      What does the existence of these kind of poverty traps indicate for a
      sparing/sharing dichotomy? 
      What could be done to eliminate the poverty 
      trap(s)? What would be the (unintended) consequences of these solutions?
      % is this a project instead?
      
\item Section \ref{sec:land_and_how_it_is_used} lists the need for resources as
      one of the drivers for land use. 
      Of course, many of the minerals that we ``need'' are available from extra-planetary 
      sources.
      What would be the sustainability implications of a move to extra-planetary 
      resources?
      Are there social consequences associated with moving wealth away from owning 
      land to owning space rocks, intellectual property, or just plain-old money?
      Are there negative externalities (negative consequences to other people) 
      from owning land? 
      Are there positive externalities to owning land (benefits that accrue to 
      others for free)?

\item The Great Green Wall is a desert-fighting project in Africa. The aim is to
      stop the south-ward advance of the Sahara desert. 
      Initially, the plan was to plant a swath of trees ten miles wide across 
      the whole continent.
      What has proven more effective is a change in land management techniques.
      With reference to Figure~\ref{fig:CarbonStorage}, discuss the importance of
      this project. \label{question:green_wall}

\item What do you think of as a more sustainable pattern of land use, urban or rural?
      What is the most impactful thing that could be done to make each more energy efficient?
      What is the most impactful way to enable each pattern of land use to be more effective?
      (What does ``effective'' or ``efficient'' mean to you in the context of
      this question?)

\item Describe where you live.
      Is it urban, suburban, rural, or would you describe it in some other way?
      What do you like about the environment in which you live?
      How would you make it different if you could?
      How do you notice the land-sharing versus land-sparing in your environment?

\item Reflect on the statement ``our investments reflect our values'' as applied to
      urban, suburban, and rural living.
      
\item In a land sparing-versus-sharing dichotomy, what are some things a city 
      could do, with respect to food, specifically, to \emph{spare} more land?
      What are some things it could do (with respect to food) to \emph{share}?
      
\item Some species (generalists) do well with land sharing. Generalists include
      red-tailed hawks, pigeon, deer, raccoons, and squirrels.
      Other species do not coexist as well with humans. 
      Examples of these include wolves, wolverine, and grizzly bears.
      \begin{enumerate}
      \item How do we decide (and who makes the decisions) about how much land we share and
      how much land we spare?
      \item What does land sharing versus land sparing say about our conservation priorities?
      \end{enumerate}
      As context for discussion, consider the case of the cougar struck and 
      killed on a Connecticut highway about 70 miles from New York City on June 11, 2011. 
      The cougar had traveled to Connecticut from South Dakota, a trip of 
      at least 1500 miles.
      In March of 2011, the U.S.\ Fish and Wildlife Service had declared the Eastern 
      cougar extinct. 
      As of 2018, the species no longer receives protection under the Endangered 
      Species Act (because it is extinct).
      The classification of the Eastern cougar as a separate subspecies is based
      on a 1946 taxonomy that recognizes 15 distinct subspecies of cougar in 
      North America.
      However, modern genetic testing indicates that \emph{all} North American cougars
      are a single species.
      Ironically, the 1982 U.S.\ Fish and Wildlife Service \emph{Eastern cougar
      recovery plan} is ``subject to modification as dictated by new findings and 
      and changes in species status and completion of tasks described in the plan.
      Goals and objectives will be attained and funds expended contingent upon 
      appropriations, priorities, and other budgetary constraints.''
      Ironically, because the U.S.\ Fish and Wildlife Service has chosen not to
      revisit the 1948 classification.
      All of this is to say that our decision not to \emph{share} land with the 
      cougar is a choice, but we could well make a different choice.
      We have already, in effect, chosen not to \emph{spare} cougar habitat, given
      the animal's large range.
      
\item What is a city's most important infrastructure and why?
      How much is it worth?
      
\item Strong Towns claims that parking minimums are set too high; see P10.\ref{project:STBFparking}
      below.
      What would be an appropriate minimum? 
      Does it depend on location or some other factor?
      If parking failure is defined as a patron arriving at the parking lot only
      to find it already full, how much parking failure should we design for?
      Contrast this to drainage and flood prevention.
      Infrastructure is built to handle storm events of a defined size with the 
      knowledge that larger storms do sometimes occur. 
      Why is it acceptable to design for failure in the storm water case but not
      in the parking case?
      
\item What do you ``go to town'' for? 
      That is, what unique or special attractions bring you into the densest 
      urban environments?
      How much time do you spend in urban versus rural areas? Why?
      
\item Think of some ways to increase population density. 
      What population density would you consider to be too high?  Why?

\item No one ever said, ``Hey, let's go sit next to the freeway and watch it for the 
      afternoon.'' 
      What are some elements of urban infrastructure that \emph{are} inherently interesting? 
      Are there any? What makes them special?
      
\item In contrast to the previous question, it has been said that ``transportation 
      creates places worth going to.''
      Under what circumstances do you think this is true? 
      Can you give examples?

\end{questions}


