\begin{projects}

\item Research restoring/regrowing/sustainable yield tropical, temperate, or boreal forests/woodlands.

\item Research restoring/regrowing temperate grasslands. Be sure to pay attention
      to the role of grazing herds.

\item Research the field of urban planning.  How has it changed over time?  
      What are its current goals?  
      How is sustainability more prominent today than 50 years ago?
      
\item Strong Towns claims 
      (\href{https://www.strongtowns.org/journal/2020/5/14/americas-growth-ponzi-scheme-md2020}{here} and 
      \href{https://www.strongtowns.org/journal/2021/4/6/pueblo-west}{here}, for example) 
      that dense, walkable downtowns maximize property tax revenue, while 
      suburban sprawl is unsustainable because it doesn't generate enough tax 
      revenue to pay for the maintenance on its own infrastructure.
      Spot check these claims with data from your local area. 
      In the U.S., property tax rolls are public. 
      Finding maintenance costs may be more difficult. 
      Try talking to your local officials such as the city engineer, assessor, 
      and/or reading your municipality's budget.
      
\item Participate in Strong Towns's \href{https://www.strongtowns.org/blackfridayparking}{Black Friday parking event}
      on social media. 
      Basically, the idea is that most parking lots are drastically 
      oversized and, therefore, a waste of land that could otherwise be used for 
      economically productive activities.
      The social media campaign is to photo document the extent of unused parking
      capacity on Black Friday, the busiest shopping day of the year.
      \label{project:STBFparking}

\item Urban planning can look very different in a growing economy (such as China) 
      compared to an established economy (such as the United Kingdom).  
      Compare and contrast the questions urban planners face and the goals for urban 
      planning in each type of economy.

\item There is a well-known field called ``urban planning.''  
      But much less attention is paid to ``rural planning.''
      Compare and contrast urban and rural planning.  
      (Hint: Other terms to be aware of include ``landscape architecture,'' 
      ``ecological science,'' and ``geographical information systems (GIS).''
      A starting point might be to consider the system in France that restricts
      building in agricultural areas. 
      Start by looking at ``Plan Local d’Urbanisme'' (PLU) or the more limited 
      ``Carte Communale.''

      
\end{projects}


